Maybe it's Christmas coming up and all? <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">I. &quot;Impact Initiated Fusion Drive&quot;</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
I'm not sure I understand this concept. Are we talking about a jet or a sail or some kind of Inertial Confinement Fusion device &quot;fed&quot; from behind the vehicle? From where, destination or starting-point, and what is supposed to fire/maintain the &quot;pellet train&quot;? <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">II. Antimatter Driven Sail</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.space.com/businesstechnology/technology/antimatter_sail_021029.html">www.space.com/businesstechnology/technology/antimatter_sail_021029.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Agree it sounds nice, especially since the sail area can be brought down a lot in size, although it's probably rather far off considered current antimatter production capacity, costs and storing problems (although you need modest amounts for the 250 AU spaceship in question). Fusion should be closer.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Again, I ask the wiser persons in that forum - what is the max V achievable theoretically with such timid fission drive?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
- Well, I'm just a space enthusiast, but theoretical maximum velocity of any propulsion system is a matter of enthalpy, that is energy per unit mass. This was probably what Tim1965 was hinting at in his reply. For nuclear fission the enthalpy is 82 million MJ/kg. Maximum theorethical exhaust velocity is twice the square root of the enthalpy, meaning 12,800 km/s (although I have no way to prove this, I've just read it in a book). Since about twice the exhaust velocity is possible for a reaction driven spaceship, you'll end up with a final velocity of 25,600 km/s, or about 8% of lightspeed.<br>
This does not include breaking at your destination, however, which using the same energy source would cut your max attainable velocity in exactly half, or 4% lightspeed.<br>
<br>
Now, since the antimatter sail is a dual reaction system, the enthalpy of matter/antimatter annilhilation should also be mentioned. This is no less than 90 billion MJ/kg. This translates into an exhaust velocity of 300,000 km/s given Einstein's formula - or rather the speed of light (we are talking about 100% efficient matter/energy conversion). The max theoretical velocity of an antimatter spaceship is thus twice the speed of light.<br>
<br>
Of course this is theoretical and has no bearing on propulsion systems that can be physically designed (a spaceship is more than its fuel and 100% efficiency is never attainable).<br>
To state an example, gas core nuclear thermal rockets typically achieve an exhaust velocity of about 50 km/s. This should be compared with the enthalpy of fission equalling a potential exhaust velocity of 12,800 km/s.<br>
<br>
Too bad, I'm not knowledgeable enough to extrapolate on the capabilities of the antimatter sail or how to do it, even if I knew roughly in detail how it was designed, but a few restrictions seem readily discernible.<br>
1) Although there are no complicated magnetically confined reaction chambers, the spaceship would still have to carry along its fuel, reaction mass (uranium-235) and antimatter  gas ejection system.<br>
2) As in all matter/antimatter annihilations most of the energy would be lost to space before it could push the sail in the form of gamma rays, neutrinos and other uncharged particles.<br>
3) What size of annhiliations would be possible and still keep the sail intact? Seems like very low nano numbers to me. Doesn’t this imply that we are dealing with very low energy levels (that of course needs to be compared to the mass it’s trying to push)?<br>
4) The article maintained that the fission reactions, rather than the matter/antimatter annhilations were the important source of thrust. In consequence, or as far as I can tell at least, we are principally restricted to an exhaust velocity well inside the fission enthalpy area, making the ship unsuitable for interstellar travel.<br>
<br>
As the designer himself hoped, the design in question would eventually be able to reach a velocity of 116 km/s.<br>
<br>
