About the impact fusion: <br>
1.Several months ago I found and information that if LiD-pellets are colided with total speed of 200 km/s a fusion in the matterial would occur. So this is a mechanism which do not depends from fission explosion the high fusion starting temperature to be reached.<br>
2.the other point is the concept the fuel for the ship to be gathered from the interstellar medium, not to be brought by - the old idea of the Bussard ram-jet. Recent explorations of the density and composition and ionisation of the interstellar medium, ruther reject the feasibility of the concept the ship to scoop it`s fuel from space en route.<br>
3.Hence if such externally fed scheme is not possible from non-processed natural sources, we come to the conclusion and synthesis with the also old idea for artificial external supply with energy of the transport vehicle. <br>
4.Now we agree that the nuclear energy could be easier harnesed in form of explosions, which means small and numerous, better than huge ones, in terms of acceleration management.<br>
<br>
So, combinig the ideas for MagSail Orion, Forward`s for sollar assist, Forrest Bishops`s for mass projectors and meso-particle beams, that`s the way I see such scheme:<br>
<br>
Put a sollar powered factory on light elements`-rich asteroid (NEO - easier to reach and 'land' than the Moon). It produces uniform pellets of Lid or other fusion-able composition from local resources. With rotational mechanical devices it could fire billions of tonnes of them in certain direction (towards a choosen star) with velocity of dozens of km/s and VERY high ballistic coefficient (i.e. slight dispersion). The pellet beam forms uninterrupted 'rail' or 'wake' of fuel long as billions of km as necesarry, very straith, and in the chosen direction. The pellets covers are from magnetically active material. <br>
From other or the same asteroid with mass driver in forded state fire towards the sun the actual ship/probe with several hundreds of km/s. According to Forward such way through gravity assist the ship could reach percents of the speed of light. After reaching point where it is actually 'climbing' withy the stolen speed the ship unfold in MagSail and rides the previously put beam of pellets as a ring moving on cable. Magnetically scoops the pellets in focus, where they collide with enough speed to cause impact fusion mini-explosions. Half of the 'debris' is moving in the direction of flight  through the ring as some form of hyperintensive 'solar wind' with speed of several dozens of thousands of km/s. The MagSail caches this 'wind'.<br>
<br>
It all sounds rather complicated but indeed the design avoids many obstacles in the similar schemes.  No huge lasers or particle beam accelerators, no huge onboard machinery. What you need in the diferent stages of acceleration is left behind... <br>
The one-way probe has jast to redirect the pellets in angular collision course behind it, after they pass the ring. All the time the ring is moving faster than the beam`s pellets. So, really it feds from infront. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=astronuc>Astronuc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/8/04 7:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=378.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Impact fusion and antimatter</span><hr size=1> I assume by &quot;impact&quot; fusion, one is referring to &quot;intertial confinement&quot;.<br>
<br>
Whether a fusion reactor uses inertial confinement or plasma, both systems require huge structures.  Intertial confinement requires a high energy source - lasers or particle beams - to blast the fusion fuel target.  Plasma systems require magnetic confinement systems.   Both imply lots of 'dead' mass, i.e. no light weight (correct term is light mass) propulsion system here.<br>
<br>
As for anti-matter, before one goes out to invest in such a system, one should calculate the production rate of anti-protons in today's facilities.<br>
<br>
Let me add this - I see a lot of equations thrown out in this forum, but some are taken straight from rocket dynamics (based on classical mechanics) and are not corrected for relativistic dynamics - hence some conclusions or inferences are completely wrong!  I don't want to spoil the fun, but be careful with the math.<br>
<br>
Take a look at Avogadro's number - ~6E23 atoms/g-mole.  It would take 1E20 sec to make 1 gram of anti-protons with a production rate of 1e3 per sec, or 1E17 sec at a rate of 1e6 per sec.   There are approximately 3.15576E7 sec/yr.  So, roughly one gram of anti-hydrogen every 1E16 yrs - at 1e3 /er sec.   Remember the half-life of the universe is on the order of 1e12 yrs.<br>
<br>
Its been a couple of decades since I did some basic scoping calcs for anti-matter systems, so I contacted Fermilab about their current max. production rate, and I will post it once I get a response. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=astronuc>Astronuc</A> at: 2/8/04 1:14 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=karov>karov</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 33<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/9/04 4:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=378.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Impact fusion</span><hr size=1> Yes, it`s kind of inertial confinement. But in the classic systems the compression of the pellets is acheived by powerfull beams of particles or photons, demanding the ship power aggreagate to include heavy machinery or transforming devices if the energy is supplied outwards.<br>
Here the pellets compress eachother in collision wit enough kinetic energy fusion to occur. The necesarry velocity is about 100km/s each if LiD is used. <br>
Imagine a mag-sail. It moves with several hundred to thousand km/s after Forward`s sollar assist maneuver, like a ring arrownd cable - the beam of LiD-pellets. The pellets are with magnetically active covers. Interaction with the mag-sail colimates them in a focus behind the vehicle, where they collide and fuse. The produced plasma expanding with several dozens of km/s pushes the mag-sail allong it`s trajectory. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=astronuc>Astronuc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/9/04 3:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=378.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Impact fusion</span><hr size=1> I am very skeptical of colliding LiD pellets, especially at 200 km/sec!<br>
<br>
How would you propose that two LiD pellets collide perfectly head-on.  They have to be guided to each other at 100 km/s, and presumably the guiding mechanism would be destroyed in the fusion blast being used to provide propulsion.  This is one problem in inertial confinement - timing the next pellet so as not to be affected by the detonation of the first - so one ends up with a pulsed system.<br>
<br>
Not only that - they have to be accelerated from presumably standstill or perhaps they are stored in a &quot;mighty big&quot; storage ring at what velocity I can't imagine.  If in a storage ring, the pellets have to be deflected - strong force field required!<br>
<br>
What is the mass of one of these LiD pellets?  Back in the days when I did fusion engineering, we did not consider colliding pellets of LiD. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=karov>karov</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 36<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/10/04 2:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=378.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   the pellets</span><hr size=1> 200 km/s is the minimum required velocity. That means in direct course collision. So, it`s not possible they to strike eachother perfectly head on, but under certain angle. And not just two pellets. Imagine a stream of pellets which pass through the ring of mag-sail, which magnetically focuses them in a point behind the vehicle, where the colisions/fusion explosions occur. The resulting plasma pushes the system. In such 'wholesale' scheme it`s not necesarry the precision guiding of the pellets. The pellets are not stored onbard but are interacted with the ships mag-field comming infront the vehicle previously accelerated from external source. The mass of the pellets is arbitrary, accoirding to their accelerator properties and power. It`s like a Bussard ram-jet, but without the necessity the ship to achieve 30000km/s in order to process interstellar hidrogen, but the fuel itself is accelerated to such/or lower/ velocities, toward the reciever ship`s front end. The pellets could be nanoparticles, accelerated by Forrest Bishop`s electrostatic drive. He states velocities of 10%c are feasible with this concept. <br>
<br>
In closed confinement vesses with minimal size it`s not plausible to consider colliding pellets, but a kind of mag-sail is proper tech for managing such stream colision and fusion.<br>
<br>
I`d call it Magnetic Lense Ship. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=astronuc>Astronuc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/10/04 7:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=378.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: the pellets</span><hr size=1> The mass of the pellets is important!  That will determine the effective yield (available energy) of the fusion source.  In addition, the mass of the pellets provides the momentum when the fusion products collide with the collider plate (if that is the concept) or are deflected with magnetic confinement.  <br>
<br>
Either way, you will need two streams of pellets - co-linear and traveling in opposite directions to the same ignition point (assuming one wants to maintain a constant geometry in the propulsion system).  To avoid interaction between subsequent pellets, pairs of pellets would have to be time just right to avoid interaction of the prior plasma ignition.<br>
<br>
If you want to test the concept, take two rifles about 10 m apart and aimed at each other.  Adjusting for gravity and air (unless you do it in a vacuum), see how often you can get two bullets to collide (and collide head on).  Also, take a look at Rutherford's experiment on trying to collide alpha particles with atomic nulcei.<br>
<br>
You might want to calculate how much energy and force are required to operate the pellet collision system, and then figure out how and where this energy and force is produced.  Even if you harness the fusion energy from the microexplosions, you still need an initiation source to get the first one going.<br>
<br>
And somehow, I can't imagine laying a out a trail of pellets in a stream aimed at a planet or star.  Other than Bussard's ramjet and those using solar energy or external electromagnetic (laser/maser) or particle beams, most designs I have seen store the fuel (energy source on board).<br>
<br>
By the way, if this stuff was so easy and economical, we we would already have fusion power plants in operation! <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showPrevMessage?topicID=378.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showNextMessage?topicID=378.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=378.topic&index=8><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.emailToFriend?topicID=378.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.threadControl?topicID=378.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/space/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=378.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://p068.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=378.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/unsubscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to stop receiving email notification of replies"> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies</a> <br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://p068.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum 